<p>
  Base64 encoding lets you embed an image directly inside HTML, CSS, JSON, or any text file — with no separate image file or HTTP request. Here is how to convert any image to Base64 for free.
</p>

<h2>What is a Base64 Image?</h2>

<p>
  A Base64 image is a text string representation of an image file. Instead of referencing an image via a URL (<code>src="/images/logo.png"</code>), you embed the full image data as a string:
</p>
<pre><code>&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUg..."&gt;</code></pre>
<p>
  The <code>data:</code> URL scheme (also called a data URI) tells the browser to decode the Base64 string directly into an image without fetching any external file.
</p>

<h2>When to Use Base64 Images</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Inline SVG icons and small logos:</strong> Embedding a 500-byte icon as Base64 saves an HTTP round trip.</li>
  <li><strong>Email templates:</strong> Some email clients block external images. Embedding images as Base64 ensures they always display.</li>
  <li><strong>API payloads:</strong> Sending an image via a JSON REST API — Base64 is the standard way to include binary data in a JSON body.</li>
  <li><strong>Single-file HTML documents:</strong> Creating a self-contained HTML file that includes its own images.</li>
</ul>

