<h2>How to Use the Base64 Output</h2>

<h3>In HTML</h3>
<pre><code>&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,YOUR_BASE64_HERE" alt="Logo" /&gt;</code></pre>

<h3>In CSS</h3>
<pre><code>.logo &#123;
  background-image: url("data:image/png;base64,YOUR_BASE64_HERE");
&#125;</code></pre>

<h3>In JSON</h3>
<pre><code>&#123;
  "image": "data:image/jpeg;base64,YOUR_BASE64_HERE"
&#125;</code></pre>

<h2>Limitations</h2>

<p>
  Base64 strings are 33% larger than the original binary file. Browsers also cannot cache inline Base64 images separately. For anything over 10 KB, a separate image file served with proper cache headers will always be faster and more efficient.
</p>

